00:19:36.752 --> 00:19:37.785
It knows it's you.

531
00:19:37.785 --> 00:19:39.527
It will open the doors for you.

532
00:19:39.527 --> 00:19:41.605
It will then allow you to drive that car

533
00:19:41.605 --> 00:19:43.602
to wherever you wanted to go.

534
00:19:43.602 --> 00:19:45.738
You book it for a set amount of time.

535
00:19:45.738 --> 00:19:47.480
There are penalties if you don't return it

536
00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:49.012
to where it's supposed to be.

537
00:19:49.012 --> 00:19:50.243
If you're involved in an accident,

538
00:19:50.243 --> 00:19:51.485
well, it knows.

539
00:19:51.485 --> 00:19:54.353
It has these sort of OnStar capabilities.

540
00:19:54.353 --> 00:19:56.048
They will come and deal with it.

541
00:19:56.048 --> 00:19:57.081
But the beauty of this is

542
00:19:57.081 --> 00:19:59.252
we're sharing the vehicle.

543
00:19:59.252 --> 00:20:01.017
Keep that in your head for awhile.

544
00:20:01.017 --> 00:20:02.456
If we have driver-less cars,

545
00:20:02.456 --> 00:20:04.488
and we're prepared to share vehicles,

546
00:20:04.488 --> 00:20:06.334
and we create a network of roads

547
00:20:06.334 --> 00:20:08.993
that maybe move far quicker than we do today,

548
00:20:08.993 --> 00:20:11.663
if technology allows us to build super-light vehicles

549
00:20:11.663 --> 00:20:14.473
that will travel very fast in safety,

550
00:20:14.473 --> 00:20:16.934
maybe we'll choose not to own our own cars,

551
00:20:16.934 --> 00:20:19.779
but to call up a device, a pod if you like,

552
00:20:19.779 --> 00:20:22.449
that will take us from A to B at anytime.

553
00:20:22.449 --> 00:20:24.863
As long as there are enough of them available to us,

554
00:20:24.863 --> 00:20:26.652
we may choose not to own our own car

555
00:20:26.652 --> 00:20:30.089
because, financially that becomes very wasteful.

556
00:20:30.089 --> 00:20:33.955
I mean, building a car uses a lot of materials.

557
00:20:33.955 --> 00:20:35.325
If we could share them,

558
00:20:35.325 --> 00:20:37.415
it would change our way of life.

559
00:20:37.415 --> 00:20:39.690
I think there's a lot of barriers that we have to overcome

560
00:20:39.690 --> 00:20:42.662
before the mainstream is prepared to get rid of their car.

561
00:20:42.662 --> 00:20:44.694
However, I think the day could come

562
00:20:44.694 --> 00:20:48.131
when the advantages to us, of sharing those vehicles,

563
00:20:48.131 --> 00:20:50.069
as long as they're always available to us,

564
00:20:50.069 --> 00:20:51.741
would be there.

565
00:20:51.741 --> 00:20:53.111
You wouldn't need a garage.

566
00:20:53.111 --> 00:20:54.178
You wouldn't need to park it.

567
00:20:54.178 --> 00:20:55.223
You don't need to service it.

568
00:20:55.223 --> 00:20:56.231
You don't need to insure it.

569
00:20:56.231 --> 00:20:57.949
You do not need to fill it with gas.

570
00:20:57.949 --> 00:21:01.212
And it gets you from A to B quickly and safely.

571
00:21:01.212 --> 00:21:03.116
Of course, that changes other industries.

572
00:21:03.116 --> 00:21:04.915
The pizza delivery boy.

573
00:21:04.915 --> 00:21:07.121
The pizza arrives in a pod.

574
00:21:07.121 --> 00:21:08.224
We don't need a whole car.

575
00:21:08.224 --> 00:21:11.162
Maybe we have mini-pods that use the same circuitry

576
00:21:11.162 --> 00:21:13.460
or the same infrastructure that will deliver goods

577
00:21:13.460 --> 00:21:16.665
and services around in, not real time,

578
00:21:16.665 --> 00:21:18.929
but as fast as we can make them work.

579
00:21:18.929 --> 00:21:21.402
I mean, some people have said we might build a city

580
00:21:21.402 --> 00:21:23.538
with an underground infrastructure

581
00:21:23.538 --> 00:21:26.313
of these fast-moving electromagnetic pods

582
00:21:26.313 --> 00:21:28.077
that can deliver goods and services

583
00:21:28.077 --> 00:21:30.016
around the city very quickly.

584
00:21:30.016 --> 00:21:31.549
So, you don't need a fridge anymore.

585
00:21:31.549 --> 00:21:33.987
If you need to cook, you will call-up your ingredients

586
00:21:33.987 --> 00:21:35.786
and they'll be there in five minutes.

587
00:21:35.786 --> 00:21:37.656
I think we're well into the future here.

588
00:21:37.656 --> 00:21:39.954
But the idea of first moving to cars

589
00:21:39.954 --> 00:21:41.359
that drive themselves,

590
00:21:41.359 --> 00:21:44.122
and secondly, maybe sharing a device

591
00:21:44.122 --> 00:21:47.060
or a pod that will take us from A to B

592
00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:48.534
are certainly there.

593
00:21:48.534 --> 00:21:51.936
If it's a true network, those pods may join together

594
00:21:51.936 --> 00:21:53.503
so that you're not using as much energy

595
00:21:53.503 --> 00:21:55.640
for people who are going to the same place.

596
00:21:55.640 --> 00:21:58.101
Ultimately, maybe, you get into a pod

597
00:21:58.101 --> 00:22:00.643
to go to the airport and you can surround yourself

598
00:22:00.643 --> 00:22:02.931
in your pod with everything you need.

599
00:22:02.931 --> 00:22:04.974
You travel with your luggage.

600
00:22:04.974 --> 00:22:05.984
You go on a plane.

601
00:22:05.984 --> 00:22:08.712
You travel to a remote destination.

602
00:22:08.712 --> 00:22:12.184
You arrive and it's a painless experience,

603
00:22:12.184 --> 00:22:15.179
surrounded by the entertainment that you choose.

604
00:22:15.179 --> 00:22:17.954
That leads to another interesting story

605
00:22:17.954 --> 00:22:19.487
that I'd like to tell you.

606
00:22:19.487 --> 00:22:21.862
I attended an innovation workshop

607
00:22:21.862 --> 00:22:24.231
where the tutor came up to us and said,

608
00:22:24.231 --> 00:22:26.239
"I've got an idea.

609
00:22:26.239 --> 00:22:28.341
"Air travel, people don't like it.

610
00:22:28.341 --> 00:22:32.068
"They don't like the fact that, generally speaking,

611
00:22:32.068 --> 00:22:33.310
"it can be bumpy.

612
00:22:33.310 --> 00:22:35.040
"You're cramped into a small space

613
00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:36.212
"for a long period of time,

614
00:22:36.212 --> 00:22:38.302
"sharing everybody elses' germs

615
00:22:38.302 --> 00:22:40.369
"and it's an unpleasant experience.

616
00:22:40.369 --> 00:22:42.215
"Herded around like cattle.

617
00:22:42.215 --> 00:22:44.049
"What if I picked you up from your home

618
00:22:44.049 --> 00:22:45.721
"and I gave you an injection?

619
00:22:45.721 --> 00:22:47.683
"I put you in a little pod and at the bottom

620
00:22:47.683 --> 00:22:49.262
"of the pod was your luggage.

621
00:22:49.262 --> 00:22:51.828
"You go to sleep in a air conditioned environment.

622
00:22:51.828 --> 00:22:53.151
"We then take you to the airport.

623
00:22:53.151 --> 00:22:54.928
"We stack you ten deep on a plane,

624
00:22:54.928 --> 00:22:56.263
"all fully air conditioned.

625
00:22:56.263 --> 00:22:58.062
"Your heart is monitored.

626
00:22:58.062 --> 00:23:00.187
"I will fly you to where you're going.

627
00:23:00.187 --> 00:23:01.789
"At the other end I could wake you up

628
00:23:01.789 --> 00:23:02.962
"with an injection."

629
00:23:02.962 --> 00:23:04.471
<v Voiceover>Doesn't sound warm and fuzzy</v>

630
00:23:04.471 --> 00:23:06.538
to begin with, but I can see where you're headed.

631
00:23:06.538 --> 00:23:07.246
(laughs)

632
00:23:07.246 --> 00:23:08.999
<v ->We all looked at him in astonishment.</v>

633
00:23:08.999 --> 00:23:11.182
I said, "There is no way I'm getting on a plane like that."

634
00:23:11.182 --> 00:23:14.282
I want to be around if anything happens.

635
00:23:14.282 --> 00:23:18.206
It was fun because it's actually very easy to defend that.

636
00:23:18.206 --> 00:23:20.156
No terrorism because nobody's alive--

637
00:23:20.156 --> 00:23:22.153
Well, hopefully, we're alive.

638
00:23:22.153 --> 00:23:23.628
<v Voiceover>Nobody's conscious. (laughs)</v>

639
00:23:23.628 --> 00:23:26.426
<v ->Nobody's conscious enough to do any damage.</v>

640
00:23:26.426 --> 00:23:28.864
There are a lot of safety things

641
00:23:28.864 --> 00:23:30.234
that we could keep from happening.

642
00:23:30.234 --> 00:23:31.197
Deep vein thrombosis.

643
00:23:31.197 --> 00:23:33.473
You're a lot better lying down than you are sitting

644
00:23:33.473 --> 00:23:35.133
on a plane for long periods of time.

645
00:23:35.133 --> 00:23:37.002
And you always arrive refreshed.

646
00:23:37.002 --> 00:23:39.742
On the other hand, we're just not ready for it.

647
00:23:39.742 --> 00:23:41.669
There's a slow rate of change of technology

648
00:23:41.669 --> 00:23:43.248
that people will accept.

649
00:23:43.248 --> 00:23:44.607
Maybe the biggest barrier

650
00:23:44.607 --> 00:23:47.492
to us accepting technology advances is us.

651
00:23:47.492 --> 00:23:48.450
It's the rate at which

652
00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:51.225
we can effectively use that technology.

653
00:23:51.225 --> 00:23:52.525
<v Voiceover>Where are you seeing some</v>

654
00:23:52.525 --> 00:23:54.858
of the chaos at this period in history.

655
00:23:54.858 --> 00:23:56.728
Because this is a major issue.

656
00:23:56.728 --> 00:24:00.060
Technology is changing so quickly

657
00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:02.091
and industries are starting to dry up

658
00:24:02.091 --> 00:24:03.868
as others are being given birth to.

659
00:24:03.868 --> 00:24:07.072
How do you notice, when you're advising a company?

660
00:24:07.072 --> 00:24:08.628
How do you see us beginning

661
00:24:08.628 --> 00:24:11.739
to strategically adapt to all of this?

662
00:24:11.739 --> 00:24:14.514
<v ->We have to be aware of our complete surroundings.</v>

663
00:24:14.514 --> 00:24:16.813
As a company, you need to look at not only

664
00:24:16.813 --> 00:24:19.785
who your customers are and where they are headed,

665
00:24:19.785 --> 00:24:20.946
but you also need to look back and say,

666
00:24:20.946 --> 00:24:22.583
"Who's supplying me?"

667
00:24:22.583 --> 00:24:24.615
Because they may go out of business.

668
00:24:24.615 --> 00:24:26.577
Because there are economic loads.

669
00:24:26.577 --> 00:24:28.260
There is an economic factor that you have

670
00:24:28.260 --> 00:24:31.360
to achieve to manufacture certain goods and services.

671
00:24:31.360 --> 00:24:33.589
If you're using a portion of somebody's output

672
00:24:33.589 --> 00:24:35.633
but the rest of it is made redundant

673
00:24:35.633 --> 00:24:38.338
because their customer doesn't actually need

674
00:24:38.338 --> 00:24:40.331
that product anymore, you have to be aware

675
00:24:40.331 --> 00:24:43.036
that your supply chain can change drastically.

676
00:24:43.036 --> 00:24:45.010
So you have to be up to speed on what's happening

677
00:24:45.010 --> 00:24:47.169
both looking behind you at your suppliers

678
00:24:47.169 --> 00:24:49.306
as well as looking forwards into the market

679
00:24:49.306 --> 00:24:52.580
at how the consumer or customer is going to behave.

680
00:24:52.580 --> 00:24:55.041
I think that the advent of the PDA

681
00:24:55.041 --> 00:24:56.887
that we were describing earlier needs

682
00:24:56.887 --> 00:24:58.953
to be looked at more closely.

683
00:24:58.953 --> 00:25:02.495
That device can be your office away from home.

684
00:25:02.495 --> 00:25:03.923
It can be your office anywhere.

685
00:25:03.923 --> 00:25:06.662
If we are wirelessly connected to our data,

686
00:25:06.662 --> 00:25:08.694
whether that be Word files, Excel files,

687
00:25:08.694 --> 00:25:12.094
video, music as we were talking about earlier,

688
00:25:12.094 --> 00:25:14.174
if I have access to that anywhere,

689
00:25:14.174 --> 00:25:17.402
I can be online and effectively productive anywhere

690
00:25:17.402 --> 00:25:18.876
in the world.

691
00:25:18.876 --> 00:25:21.012
My friends all carry the Blackberry today.

692
00:25:21.012 --> 00:25:22.510
Wirelessly connected to the Internet,

693
00:25:22.510 --> 00:25:24.681
they get Email 24 hours a day.

694
00:25:24.681 --> 00:25:26.016
They can use it wherever they are

695
00:25:26.016 --> 00:25:28.420
in the world that gets a wireless signal.

696
00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:31.949
That increases the megahertz or the frequency

697
00:25:31.949 --> 00:25:34.190
with which we're able to operate the economy.

698
00:25:34.190 --> 00:25:36.129
Gone are the days where we'd send a letter

699
00:25:36.129 --> 00:25:37.185
asking for a quote.

700
00:25:37.185 --> 00:25:38.590
It would come back.

701
00:25:38.590 --> 00:25:40.900
The speed that the economy works at today

702
00:25:40.900 --> 00:25:43.396
with Email, we can make informed decisions

703
00:25:43.396 --> 00:25:45.033
very, very quickly.

704
00:25:45.033 --> 00:25:46.102
We have to be aware

705
00:25:46.102 --> 00:25:48.667
that not only can we make informed decisions quickly,

706
00:25:48.667 --> 00:25:50.641
our customers make informed decisions.

707
00:25:50.641 --> 00:25:52.870
If we're not the leading player in a market,

708
00:25:52.870 --> 00:25:56.040
and we don't have a price differential

709
00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:58.547
to cope with the fact that we don't have the best product,

710
00:25:58.547 --> 00:26:00.916
it's highly likely that we'll find it very difficult

711
00:26:00.916 --> 00:26:02.216
to survive.

712
00:26:02.216 --> 00:26:04.318
Anticipating what the market will want

713
00:26:04.318 --> 00:26:07.023
is key to your future success.

714
00:26:07.023 --> 00:26:07.952
But just as we were saying

715
00:26:07.952 --> 00:26:09.821
that those individual technologies

716
00:26:09.821 --> 00:26:12.735
that we surround ourselves may be made redundant

717
00:26:12.735 --> 00:26:15.161
as we consolidate them into one device.

718
00:26:15.161 --> 00:26:18.760
That device fulfills a very interesting role in us all.

719
00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:20.630
It is our entertainment system.

720
00:26:20.630 --> 00:26:22.743
It is our communications device.

721
00:26:22.743 --> 00:26:24.310
It's always with us

722
00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:27.909
to the extent that it would be our key to our front door.

723
00:26:27.909 --> 00:26:30.942
It would be infrared, enabled our front door

724
00:26:30.942 --> 00:26:32.544
just as hotel doors are.

725
00:26:32.544 --> 00:26:35.411
We'll have some element of technology within it.

726
00:26:35.411 --> 00:26:39.579
We will embed our thumbprint or some eyeprint factor

727
00:26:39.579 --> 00:26:42.888
into the usage of that technology to keep it secure.

728
00:26:42.888 --> 00:26:47.323
If it is secure, we will totally depend on this one device.

729
00:26:47.323 --> 00:26:49.193
We may totally depend on it to the extent

730
00:26:49.193 --> 00:26:52.200
that we would like to embed it in our bodies

731
00:26:52.200 --> 00:26:54.196
so that we never lose it.

732
00:26:54.196 --> 00:26:56.867
Without it, we may become totally lost.

733
00:26:56.867 --> 00:26:59.270
This is one of the theories of networking

734
00:26:59.270 --> 00:27:01.295
that we have today is that

735
00:27:01.295 --> 00:27:03.775
if your data is available somewhere,

736
00:27:03.775 --> 00:27:04.709
you're connected.

737
00:27:04.709 --> 00:27:06.567
If you keep all your data to yourself,

738
00:27:06.567 --> 00:27:08.691
like we may do in our household PC,

739
00:27:08.691 --> 00:27:10.305
someday it will fail.

740
00:27:10.305 --> 00:27:12.255
And we're not very good at backing it up.

741
00:27:12.255 --> 00:27:14.554
So, we need to be aware that the vitality

742
00:27:14.554 --> 00:27:18.362
or the essential essence of our data is us.

743
00:27:18.362 --> 00:27:20.429
As we put more and more information

744
00:27:20.429 --> 00:27:22.867
into these devices, we're gonna feel more and more lost

745
00:27:22.867 --> 00:27:24.063
if we lose them.

746
00:27:24.063 --> 00:27:25.468
Now, that may result in us saying,

747
00:27:25.468 --> 00:27:27.139
"I don't ever want me to be separated

748
00:27:27.139 --> 00:27:29.009
"from that technology."

749
00:27:29.009 --> 00:27:30.971
At which stage we may choose to embed it

750
00:27:30.971 --> 00:27:32.666
in our bodies.

751
00:27:32.666 --> 00:27:34.744
Which lead us to a couple of other technologies

752
00:27:34.744 --> 00:27:36.497
that i'd like to talk about.

753
00:27:36.497 --> 00:27:39.376
One of which is the man-machine interface.

754
00:27:39.376 --> 00:27:42.012
I mean, today we've moved from a keyboard

755
00:27:42.012 --> 00:27:44.252
to a mouse to a little pointer

756
00:27:44.252 --> 00:27:46.756
that we may have in the middle of our laptop.

757
00:27:46.756 --> 00:27:48.788
We've started to think about new ways.

758
00:27:48.788 --> 00:27:50.262
We tried voice recognition,

759
00:27:50.262 --> 00:27:51.656
which is getting better and better.

760
00:27:51.656 --> 00:27:54.233
But we need that instant interaction

761
00:27:54.233 --> 00:27:57.100
with the computing power that we carry with us.

762
00:27:57.100 --> 00:27:59.620
People today are looking at mind interfaces.

763
00:27:59.620 --> 00:28:01.489
There are two or three things going on

764
00:28:01.489 --> 00:28:03.637
that I believe will lead us, eventually,

765
00:28:03.637 --> 00:28:06.168
to mind control over that device.

766
00:28:06.168 --> 00:28:08.107
Which may ultimately mean that we choose

767
00:28:08.107 --> 00:28:10.614
to embed that technology in our brains.

768
00:28:10.614 --> 00:28:11.984
Now, there are things that we have to overcome

769
00:28:11.984 --> 00:28:13.203
from a health perspective.

770
00:28:13.203 --> 00:28:15.049
It's never a good thing to embed anything

771
00:28:15.049 --> 00:28:17.186
in our bodies that's foreign.

772
00:28:17.186 --> 00:28:20.188
Also, if we are wirelessly connecting ourselves

773
00:28:20.188 --> 00:28:23.211
to these devices, I think the jury's still out

774
00:28:23.211 --> 00:28:24.964
on whether those wireless waves

775
00:28:24.964 --> 00:28:27.228
that are coming in and using our cell phones today

776
00:28:27.228 --> 00:28:29.399
are actually damaging us in some way.

777
00:28:29.399 --> 00:28:31.257
But let's talk about those technologies

778
00:28:31.257 --> 00:28:33.265
that I believe will drastically change the way

779
00:28:33.265 --> 00:28:35.901
we interface with technology.

780
00:28:35.901 --> 00:28:37.132
The first of which was sponsored

781
00:28:37.132 --> 00:28:39.337
by the U. S. Department of Defense.

782
00:28:39.337 --> 00:28:41.079
That, in itself, is a bit worrying.

783
00:28:41.079 --> 00:28:42.739
But we'll push that to one side.

784
00:28:42.739 --> 00:28:45.537
It started off by U. S. pilots being asked

785
00:28:45.537 --> 00:28:47.453
to move a dot across the screen

786
00:28:47.453 --> 00:28:49.148
whilst they wore a helmet configured

787
00:28:49.148 --> 00:28:50.611
with electrodes.

788
00:28:50.611 --> 00:28:53.223
They were asked to think about a list of subjects.

789
00:28:53.223 --> 00:28:55.023
One of them might have been a waterfall.

790
00:28:55.023 --> 00:28:56.660
One of them might have been going to sleep.

791
00:28:56.660 --> 00:28:58.598
One of them might have been driving a car.

